          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Steel manning is the practice of constructing the strongest, most charitable version of an opposing argument or position — the opposite of strawmanning. Rather than engaging with a weakened caricature of what your opponent believes, you engage with what they actually believe at its best. This forces you to genuinely understand the opposing view, reveals its strongest points, and dramatically improves the quality of your own thinking and decisions."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the difference between steel manning and devil's advocate?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Devil's advocate argues against a position for the sake of testing it, regardless of the arguer's actual views. Steel manning goes further: it requires genuinely understanding and constructing the best version of the opposing position — not just finding objections, but understanding why a reasonable, intelligent person would hold that view. Steel manning is more demanding and produces deeper understanding."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How does steel manning improve decision making?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Steel manning forces engagement with the strongest objections to your preferred option before committing. This surfaces information your confirmation bias would suppress, reveals weaknesses in your reasoning that need addressing, and either strengthens your conviction (because the best counter-argument didn't shake it) or changes your mind (because it should). Both outcomes improve decision quality."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can you steel man a position you strongly disagree with?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes — and this is precisely when it is most valuable. If you can only steel man positions you partially agree with, you're not doing the full exercise. The test of genuine steel manning is whether the person who holds the opposing view would recognize your representation as fair and strong. If they would say 'yes, that's a good version of my argument,' you've steel manned it."
        }
      }
    ]
  })} />

