        src={heroImage}
        alt="Steel Manning: How to Think Like Your Strongest Opponent"
        width={1200}
        height={630}
        fetchpriority="high"
        loading="eager"
      />
    </figure>

    <div class="article-body" itemprop="articleBody">

      <section>
        <h2>The Strawman Problem</h2>
        <p>When you disagree with someone — or with an idea — the tempting move is to engage with the weakest version of their position. Pick the worst argument, the most extreme interpretation, the easiest version to dismiss. Defeat it. Feel right. Move on.</p>
        <p>This is the straw man: a weakened, distorted version of an argument that's easy to knock down precisely because it isn't the real argument. It's intellectually satisfying but epistemically useless. You haven't engaged with the actual position — you've constructed a simulacrum and beaten it.</p>
        <p>The consequences aren't just rhetorical. When you make decisions based on straw-manned versions of the opposing case, you're making decisions based on a false picture of reality. You dismiss options that deserved consideration. You miss flaws in your own reasoning that better counter-arguments would have exposed. You confirm what you already believed instead of testing it.</p>
        <p>Steel manning is the opposite practice — and it is far harder, far rarer, and far more valuable.</p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What Steel Manning Actually Requires</h2>
        <p>Steel manning means constructing the best, strongest, most charitable version of an opposing position. Not a version you invented. Not a version designed to be easy to refute. The version that a thoughtful, intelligent person who holds that view would recognize as genuinely representing their argument.</p>
        <p>The test is simple and demanding: if you showed your steel man to the person who holds the opposing view, would they say "yes, that's a fair and strong representation of what I believe"? If yes, you've steel manned it. If they'd say "that's not what I mean at all," you haven't.</p>
        <p>What this requires in practice:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Genuine curiosity about why intelligent people hold the opposing view</li>
          <li>Willingness to engage with the strongest evidence and arguments on the other side</li>
          <li>Honest acknowledgment of what is genuinely uncertain or contested</li>
          <li>Resistance to the pull of motivated reasoning — the desire to find flaws rather than understand</li>
          <li>The intellectual courage to let the steel man actually challenge your position</li>
        </ul>

        <ContentBox type="highlight" title="The Charity Principle">
          Steel manning is an application of the principle of charity: interpret opposing positions in their most reasonable form before critiquing them. This isn't niceness — it's epistemic hygiene. You can only learn something from an opposing view if you engage with it honestly. A weakened caricature teaches you nothing.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Steel Manning as a Decision Tool</h2>
        <p>Outside of debate and intellectual discourse, steel manning has direct practical value for anyone making consequential decisions. The mechanism is straightforward: before committing to a choice, you must construct the strongest possible case against it.</p>
        <p>This sounds simple. It isn't. Because your confirmation bias — the tendency to seek information that confirms what you already believe — will pull you toward weak objections that are easy to dismiss. Building genuine strong objections requires active resistance to that pull.</p>
        <p>When steel manning works as a decision tool, it does two things:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>It surfaces information you would otherwise miss.</strong> The strongest objection to your preferred option contains real information about its weaknesses. If that objection is strong enough to shake your confidence, you have learned something important before committing — not after.</li>
          <li><strong>It builds justified confidence when confidence is warranted.</strong> If you've genuinely constructed the strongest possible case against your position and it doesn't change your mind, you have real grounds for confidence — not the false confidence of someone who only encountered weak objections. The decision is stress-tested.</li>
        </ol>

        <ContentBox type="info" title="Charlie Munger's Inversion">
          Charlie Munger — one of the most successful investors and thinkers of the 20th century — practiced a related technique he called inversion: "tell me where I'm going to die, so I'll never go there." Before committing to any significant decision, he would systematically build the case for why it would fail. This is steel manning applied to your own plans — and it is one of the habits most responsible for his record of avoiding catastrophic errors.
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

