      <section>
        <h2>How to Steel Man: A Practical Method</h2>

        <StepsList title="The Steel Manning Process">
          <li><strong>State the opposing position neutrally.</strong> Before building the steel man, write down the opposing view as fairly as you can — without evaluating it. "The opposing position is..." Force yourself to describe it in terms that don't reveal your disagreement.</li>
          <li><strong>Find the strongest proponents.</strong> Who holds this view most intelligently? What do the best-informed, most thoughtful advocates of this position actually say? Read them. Not their critics — them. If you can't name anyone credible who holds the view, you may not understand it well enough yet.</li>
          <li><strong>Identify the strongest evidence.</strong> What evidence genuinely supports the opposing position? What data, examples, or arguments does the best case rely on? Write these down without immediately rebutting them.</li>
          <li><strong>Build the best version.</strong> Now construct the steel man: the most compelling, coherent, well-evidenced version of the opposing view you can. Write it as if you were arguing for it, not against it. Aim for the version that would make a smart undecided person genuinely consider it.</li>
          <li><strong>Apply the recognition test.</strong> Would someone who genuinely holds this view recognize your representation as fair and strong? If yes, proceed. If not, revise until they would.</li>
          <li><strong>Engage honestly.</strong> Now respond to the steel man, not the straw man. Does your position still hold? If yes — good: your conviction is tested and justified. If no — better: you've avoided a bad decision or updated a mistaken belief before it cost you.</li>
        </StepsList>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Steel Manning in Different Contexts</h2>

        <h3>Business Strategy</h3>
        <p>Before committing to a strategic direction, steel man the case against it. Not "what are the obvious risks?" but "what is the best argument that this strategy is fundamentally wrong?" Then answer that argument. The strategy that survives a genuine steel man challenge is far more robust than one that only survived weak objections and motivated optimism.</p>

        <h3>Hiring and Personnel Decisions</h3>
        <p>When you're inclined to hire someone (or inclined not to), steel man the opposite position. What is the strongest case that you're wrong about this person? What evidence might a skeptic point to? This disciplines the confirmation bias that causes hiring managers to overlook red flags in candidates they like and overlook strengths in candidates they've pre-judged.</p>

        <h3>Negotiations</h3>
        <p>Understanding the other party's position at its strongest — not as something to be defeated, but as something to be genuinely understood — is the foundation of effective negotiation. What is the strongest version of their case? What do they need that they haven't explicitly said? Steel manning the other side's position is the fastest path to finding mutually beneficial solutions.</p>

        <h3>Personal Beliefs and Life Decisions</h3>
        <p>The most uncomfortable application: steel manning positions that challenge your own life choices. What is the strongest case that the career path you've chosen is a mistake? That the relationship you're in is wrong for you? That the belief you hold most firmly is mistaken? This is genuinely hard. It is also where the practice offers the most value — because these are the areas where motivated reasoning is strongest and the cost of error is highest.</p>

        <ContentGrid columns={2} gap="md">
          <ContentBox type="warning" title="Signs You're Strawmanning">
            — You can defeat the opposing view quickly and easily<br/>
            — The strongest proponents of the view seem obviously wrong<br/>
            — Your objection is to tone or presentation, not substance<br/>
            — You can't explain why intelligent people hold this view<br/>
            — Your "counter-argument" addresses what you wish they'd said
          </ContentBox>
          <ContentBox type="tip" title="Signs You're Steel Manning">
            — The opposing view is genuinely challenging to address<br/>
            — You can explain clearly why smart people hold this view<br/>
            — The best proponents would recognize your representation<br/>
            — Engaging with it required real effort and research<br/>
            — Your position after the exercise is more nuanced than before
          </ContentBox>
        </ContentGrid>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Steel Manning and Intellectual Humility</h2>
        <p>The deepest value of steel manning isn't tactical — it's epistemic. Practiced consistently, it gradually erodes the false certainty that prevents learning. When you develop the habit of genuinely engaging with the best opposing arguments, you accumulate evidence about how often your initial views needed revision. That evidence is humbling in the right way: it calibrates your confidence to your actual track record of being right.</p>
        <p>This is the difference between intellectual confidence and intellectual arrogance. Genuine confidence comes from having tested your positions against the best opposing arguments and finding they hold up. Arrogance comes from never having tested them seriously. Steel manning is the test.</p>
        <p>It also changes how you disagree with people. When you've genuinely tried to understand the strongest version of someone's position, your disagreement becomes more precise, more honest, and more productive. You're engaging with what they actually believe — which makes it possible for the conversation to go somewhere, rather than cycling endlessly because neither party feels understood.</p>

        <ContentBox type="tip" title="Key Takeaways">
          — Steel manning builds the strongest version of the opposing position — the opposite of strawmanning<br/>
          — The recognition test: would the person who holds this view say your representation is fair and strong?<br/>
          — As a decision tool: construct the best case against your preferred option before committing<br/>
          — Two outcomes are both valuable: a changed mind (you learned something) or a stress-tested conviction (justified confidence)<br/>
          — Find the strongest proponents of the opposing view — not its weakest representatives<br/>
          — The hardest and most valuable application: steel manning challenges to your own life choices and core beliefs
        </ContentBox>
      </section>

